  <body><![CDATA[Spenks, I read and loved your review yesterday. However, I was called away before commenting. So I begin today with morning coffee and a return to your review.<br><br>Beautiful job, first of all. Secondly--good on you for your presentation on this novel for The Big Read Program.<br><br>A tip of the hat for your connection to Faulkner's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/72228.Intruder_in_the_Dust_" title="Intruder in the Dust  by William Faulkner" rel="nofollow">Intruder in the Dust</a>. As you know, I have a particular fondness for Lawyer Gavin Stevens. ;-) Gavin and Atticus in the court room are quite similar in their approach. Stevens certainly has his share of memorable lines. However, he never had the benefit of being portrayed on the big screen by the likes of Gregory Peck.<br><br>My favorite Stevens quote does come from "IitD."<br><br><blockquote>“Some things you must always be unable to bear. Some things you must never stop refusing to bear. Injustice and outrage and dishonor and shame. No matter how young you are or how old you have got. Not for kudos and not for cash: your picture in the paper nor money in the back either. Just refuse to bear them.”</blockquote><br><br>It certainly bears some similarity to Atticus' stirring "In the name of God, do your duty."<br><br>As Ms. Lee has often done, she has contradicted herself on the source of Atticus Finch. Soon after the novel's publication she firmly stated that Atticus was based on her father, Amasa Coleman Lee, who was a small town lawyer, who was a member of the Alabama House of representatives, and who was appointed to represent two black men, a father and son, accused of murdering a store clerk. Mr. Lee, as Atticus did, served up his best defense. However, the all white jury returned verdicts of guilty. Amasa Lee represented the last two men hung in the Monroe County Jail. He was present at their execution. That case was the source of his disdain for the practice of criminal law. Who could blame him.<br><br>It was as editor of the Monroeville, Al., newspaper that Amasa Lee covered a rape case almost identical to the facts of the "Tom Robinson" case. Lee was not appointed. However he covered the case extensively. The verdict in that case was guilty. The sentence was death. Interestingly enough, a letter writing campaign, believed to have been initiated by Amasa Lee, resulted in the Defendant's sentence being commuted to life. As Miss Maudie said in the novel, "Baby steps."<br><br>As to Ms. Lee's contradiction, she subsequently said her father was <i>not</i> the source for Atticus Finch. Personally, there are too many similarities between the lives of the real Amasa Lee and the fictional Atticus Finch, for me to accept that. Rather, I chalk it up to Ms. Lee's pursuit of privacy for which she has become renowned.<br><br><a href="http://s1151.photobucket.com/user/mmcsullivan/media/MrLeeampMrPeck_zpsd69cc752.jpg.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1415371015i/11778780.jpg" alt=" photo MrLeeampMrPeck_zpsd69cc752.jpg" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></a><br><b>
  <i>Art imitates life,</i>
</b><br><br>We have very little about which we disagree. One issue is Calpurnia. I have never perceived her as an Uncle Tom character. She never bows or scrapes. She is certainly not a "Step-n-fetch-it" stereotype." She is a human being with whom Atticus confidently entrusts his children. Perhaps it is because I am a Southerner who was similarly entrusted to the care of black women when I was a child, which was not an uncommon arrangement. These women were family to me. I was taught to obey them as I would my mother or grandparents. My responses were to be "Yes, Ma'am," or "No, Ma'am." This is not meant to be a denial that racism existed in the South. It certainly did. But not in my home, nor in the homes of friends. <br><br>The novel still astonishes me to this day. It is one of those rare works to which I can return time and again with the assurance I will never be disappointed. I chalk that up to Ms. Lee's epigraph from Lamb. There is no suppose to it, really. Lawyers were children once. TKAM has inspired so many children to become not only lawyers but those who have the integrity of Atticus Finch. From time to time I return to this novel to remind myself that integrity does exist though in reality, as it does in any profession, is not always found in every individual that practices. In essence it is a return to the safe haven of childhood when all lawyers <i>were</i> Atticus Finch.<br><br>Well...it's been a long time since you and I have talked. I appreciate your having written this review very much. Should you wish to borrow a line from an old retired Southern Lawyer, feel free to do so. However, you certainly have no need to--beautifully rendered review. Would love to be at your presentation. <br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7078095.Scout__Atticus__and_Boo_A_Celebration_of_Fifty_Years_of__To_Kill_a_Mockingbird_" title='Scout, Atticus, and Boo A Celebration of Fifty Years of "To Kill a Mockingbird" rel="nofollow" by Mary McDonagh Murphy'>Scout, Atticus, and Boo: A Celebration of Fifty Years of "To Kill a Mockingbird"</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/4120488.Mary_McDonagh_Murphy" title="Mary McDonagh Murphy" rel="nofollow">Mary McDonagh Murphy</a><br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/337788.In_Search_of_Atticus_Finch" title="In Search of Atticus Finch by Mike Papantonio" rel="nofollow">In Search of Atticus Finch</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/109499.Mike_Papantonio" title="Mike Papantonio" rel="nofollow">Mike Papantonio</a><br><br><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/114408.Mockingbird_A_Portrait_of_Harper_Lee" title="Mockingbird A Portrait of Harper Lee by Charles J. Shields" rel="nofollow">Mockingbird: A Portrait of Harper Lee</a> by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/9460.Charles_J__Shields" title="Charles J. Shields" rel="nofollow">Charles J. Shields</a><br><br>"Who Was Atticus Finch?", Talmadge Boston, Texas Bar Journal, June, 2010, <a target="_blank" href="http://www.texasbar.com/AM/Template.cfm?Section=Texas_Bar_Journal&amp;Template=/CM/ContentDisplay.cfm&amp;ContentID=9585" rel="nofollow">http://www.texasbar.com/AM/Template.c...</a>]]></body>
  
